ce:section.ce:para:
The sensitivity of the CDs was evaluated by fluorescence measurements, which were taken in different concentrations of Fe3+(0.0016 µM-0.0228 µM) in CDs solution. As detailed in Fig. S12, the fluorescence intensity of CDs are sensitively and linearly decreased when Fe3+ ions are gradually added to the CDs solution. The quenching efficiency is calculated by the Stern-Volmer equation [3] as follows;
(1) F0/F = 1 + KSV [Q]
where KSV is the Stern–Volmer quenching constant, [Q] is the concentration of determined ions (Fe3+or ClO− for this study), and F and F0 are the fluorescence intensities at 430 nm in the presence and absence of determined ions, respectively. In Fig. 2c, a plot of F0/F vs [Q] indicated a good linearity (R2 = 0.99). KSV was calculated as 9.64189 µM−1. LOD was calculated by 3 s/k equation, where k is slope and s is the standard deviation. LOD was found to be 0.75 nM. The selectivity of CDs for Fe3+ detection in the presence of competing metal cations is investigated. The competitive effects of these cations are given in Fig. 3 . After the addition of the sixteen interfering metal ions separately into the CDs showed little or no significant changes in their fluorescence spectra (Fig. 3). The conclusions indicated that any of these ions in CD solutions did not prevent the determination of Fe3+ ions.
